column85: Cont1 Valve Or Device Fail Ind
column168: Description Of Events
DURING LOADING OPERATIONS, TANK OVERFLOWED.
DRUM WAS PUNCTURED AT VERY TOP SIDE OF DRUM AND VERY LITTLE CONTENTS LOST. HOLE PATCHED WITH DRUM REPAIR KIT & DRUM PLACED IN RECOVERY DRUM. FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.

RESPONSE TEAM WAS NOTIFIED AT 0140 OF A POSSIBLE HAZMAT SPILL LOCATED ON THE RAMP.  MATERIAL WAS FOUND TO BE ADHESIVE UN1133 MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP AND PLACED IN THE DISPOSAL AREA TO BE DISPOSED OF BY THE ENVIRONMENTAL AFFAIRS DEPT.

BARELLS WERE LOADED ON REAR OF TRAILER.  THEY WERE SO CLOSE TO THE REAR AND NO ROOM IN BETWEEN THAT WE COULD NOT GET THE DOCK PLATE INTO THE TRAILER.  COULD NOT GET BARREL DOLLY UNDER DRUMS AND PULLED UP ONTO DOCK WITH OUT THE DOCK PLATE.  THE DRUMS WERE SITTING ON CARDBOARD, WE USED THE LIFT TO TRY TO GET THE DRUMS UP ONTO THE DOCK.  THE CARDBOARD SLIPPED AND THE FORKS PUNCTURED TWO DRUMS OF ADHESIVE.

THE NASHVILLE, TN. POLICE REPORTED A RAIL CAR ON A SIDING JUST OUTSIDE CSXT RAIL YARD WAS SMOKING.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT WAS THE AT THE SCENE AND DETERMINED THE CAR, A RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED PHOSPHOTRICHLORIDE WAS SMOKING FROM AROUND THE HATCH.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND CSXT RESPONDED.  FERGUSON HARBOR A LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO STOP THE LEAK.  THE SHIPPER ALSO RESPONDED A TEAM.  IT WAS FOUND THAT A SIX INCH SQUARE INSPECTION PLATE HAD 2 OF 4 SECUREMENT BOLTS SLIGHTLY LOOSE ALLOWING VAPORS TO ESCAPE.  THE BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED DOWN AND THE RELEASE STOPPED.  ALL OTHER FIXTURES AND VALVES WERE INSPECTED TO ENSURE THEIR SECUREMENT BEFORE THE CAR WAS RELEASED.

DURING THE PROCESS OF "PUMP-OFF" UNLOADING INTO AN ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK, THE (3") OUTLET PLUG ON THE "LEFT-SIDE" OF THE TRUCK VIBRATED OPEN. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CLOSED THE VALVE AT THE SOURCE OF PRODUCT, BUT LOST THE PRODUCT THAT PUMPED OUT AND REMAINING PRODUCT IN THE TUBE, WHICH WAS APPROX. (90 GALLONS TOTAL).  UPON RETURN TO TERMINAL THE LOCKING ARMS (CAMLOCKS) WERE RE-INSPECTED AND REPLACED WITH NEW.

WHILE UNLOADING OUR INBOUND DRIVER SAW WHERE DRUM PUNCTURED BY WOOD PRIOR TO UNLOADING.  THE SPILLED CONTENTS AND DAMAGED DRUM WERE PUT IN A SALVAGE DRUM FOR RETURN TO SHIPPER.

column168: CARTON CONTAINING MATERIALS WAS LOADED ON REAR OF TRAILER BY DOOR POST. CARTON WAS STRUCK BY PRESUMABLY A FORKLIFT PUNCTURING CANNISTER.

WHILE UNLOADING TRIALER, ONE CARTON WAS DISCOVERED WET AND WAS ISOLATED IN THE HAZMAT BAY.  UPON INSPECTION, FOUND A LOOSE CAP ON ONE PLASTIC JUG. THE CAP WAS TIGHTENED AND THE CARTON WAS PROPERLY RECOOPERED AND OVERPACKED, THEN FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.

WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER A DRUM WAS DISCOVERED PUNCTURED AND LEAKING.  THE DRUM WAS PROPERLY RECOOPERED AND OVERPACKED INTO A NEW DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM, WITH PROPER MARKINGS AND LABELS APPLIED.  THE SALVAGE DRUM WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR CLAIM CREDIT.

BLOWN CONNECTION GASKET CAUSING SPILL DURING LOADING PROCESS ON ASPHALT. ABSORBENT BOOMS WERE USED TO STOP FLOW OF SOLVENT AFTER PUMP WAS TURNED OFF.  CORN COB ABSORBENT WAS USED TO SOAK UP ALL THE SOLVENT.  THE ABSORBENT WAS THEN SWEPT UP AND DRUMMED AND LABELED TO BE SENT FOR DISPOSAL AT SAFETY KLEEN'S RECYCLE CENTER IN DENTON TX. AT 1722 COOPER CREEK, DENTON TX., 76208.

column168: DRIVER REMOVED DUST CAP TO ATTACH HOSE AND PRODUCT CAME OUT.  THE VALVE ON THE TRAILER WAS LEFT OPEN. OIL DRY WAS APPLIED TO SOAK UP GASOLINE, AND THEN SWEPT UP AND DISPOSED OF INTO DESIGNATED BARRELS.

DOT PULLED WAGNER DRIVER OVER DUE TO A LOOSE PLACARD AND PERFORMED A ROUTINE INSPECTION. DOT BROKE SHIPPERS SEAL TO INSPECT THE CONTENTS AND DISCOVERED THAT 1 BAG WAS LEAING AND SHIPPER HAD STUFFED OLD BAG INTO THE PUNCTURE HOLE IN THE BAG.  DOT CALLED FIRE DEPT. (HAZMAT 71) WAGNER INDUSTRIES CALLED INDUSTRIAL COMPLIANCE & SAFETY INC. (ICS) ICS COLLECTED THE SPILLED PRODUCT AND PUT IT BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER.  ICS TAPED UP THE PUNCTURE IN THE CONTAINER.  WAGNER DRIVER RELEASED.

WHILE ENTERING THE TRAILER WITH THE FORKLIFT, DOCKWORKER PUNCTURED ONE CARTON WITH THE BLADE, CAUSING THE INNER CONTAINER TO RUPTURE AND MATERIAL TO SPILL.  THE AREA WAS ISOLATED AND ABSORBENT USED TO CONTAIN THE SPILLAGE.  THE DAMAGED CARTON AND THE REMAINING CONTAINERS WERE SEALED INSIDE A RECOVERY PAIL AND HELD FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.
WHILE UNLOADING DRIER SMELLED PRODUCT AND DETECTED DROPS OF PRODUCT BY DOLLIES LEGS.  DRIVER GOT OIL DRY AND PUT CONTAINER UNDER DRIP, FINISHED UNLOADING AND DRIP STOPPED.  CONSIGNEE CLEANED UP AREA.
LIQUID/VAPOR HOUSING NOT SECURED-VAPOR VALVE FOUND IN OPEN POSITION AND PLUG OUT. CLOSED VALVE-APPLIED PLUG AND SECURED COVER.

DRIVER DROVE INTO HBD INDUSTRIES AND WENT TO THE OPERATIONS FOREMAN TO VERIFYTOLUOL NEEDED. FOREMAN CHECKED HIS COMPUTER READING AND SAID HE HAD ROOM FOR900 GALLONS WHICH WOULD STILL LEAVE HIM WITH A 200 GALLON CUSHION TO THEMAXIMUM FILL MARK OF 2000 GALLONS. VERY NEAR THE 900 GALLON MARK, THE DRIVERTURNED AROUND TO UNHOOK HIS SWING HOSE TO BLOW HIS LINE OUT. AFTER DOING THIS,THE DRIVER TURNED BACK AROUND TO SEE TOLUOL RUNNING OUT OF UNDERGROUND TANK, SOHE SHUT THE PUMP OFF. NEXT TO THE TANK OPENING IS ABOUT A 3 FOOT SQUARECONCRETE CONTAINMENT AREA WHICH IS AT GROUND LEVEL, AND WHERE THE TOLUOL RAN INTO. HOLDING AREA HAD SOME WATER IN IT, WHICH FOREMAN SAID THAT HE WOULD TAKECARE OF IT AND THE SPILL. THE TANK IS EQUIPPED WITH AN OVERFILL ALARM BUT THEALARM SYSTEM DID NOT GO OFF SIGNIFYING TANK WAS GETTING FULL, FOREMAN THEN WENTTO THE COMPUTER TO SEE THE READING, AND IT SHOULD HAVE READ 2000 GALLONS.FOREMAN ADMITTED AN ERROR IN THEIR SYSTEM. A FOLLOW UP PHONE CALL TO THEFOREMAN CONFIRMED THAT THE SPILL WAS PUMPED INTO A WASTE DRUM WHICH THECUSTOMER WAS TO RECYCLE OR USE IN CLEAN UP.
WHILE DRIVER WAS UNLOADING, SOMETHING IN THE PUMP POPPED, LIQUID BEGAN COMING OUT FROM AROUND THE SHAFT.  DRIVER WAS ABLE TO CATCH MOST IN A BUCKET.

CGI DOCKMAN, MICHAEL BORRELLI, APPROACHED ME AT 1830/09 AND SAID HE FOUND THIS BOX IN THE GARBAGE CAN.  IT APPEARS THE FREIGHT WAS LOADED AT ONE TIME BUT SOME UNKNOWN PERSON MOVED IT, OR DROPPED IT, CAUSING ONE LITER BOTTLE TO BREAK.  I CLEANED UP THE SPILL AND PLACED THE CONTENTS IN A SMALL RECOVERY DRUM.

ADVISED BY CSX OPERATIONS CENTER THAT THE MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT FOUND CAR ACFX 79921 LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET ASSEMBLY IN TRACK E08 IN ERWIN YARD, ERWIN, TENN.  MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT EMPLOYEES PLACED BUCKETS AND PANS UNDER THE BOTTOM OUTLET ASSEMBLY TO COLLECT LEAKING MATERIALS. CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED FOR SHIPPER ASSISTANCE.  ASHLAND CHEMICAL REPRESENTATIVE JAMES HUNT (614) 889-3058 WAS ADVISED OF THE INCIDENT AND MADE ARRANGEMENTS WITH TENN. EASTMAN COMPANY AT KINGSPORT, TENN. TO RESPOND AND SECURE THE CAR.  EASTMAN PERSONNEL ON SCENE AND INSPECTED CAR AND FOUND THAT THE TOP OPERATING BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS OPEN APPROXIMATELY 4 TURNS.  CAR WAS SECURED AT 2115 HOURS.  ESTIMATED BY TENN. EASTMAN PERSONNEL THAT 2 1/2 GALLONS HAD LEAKED FROM THE CAR AND HAD BEEN COLLECTED IN THE BUCKETS AND PANS.  COLLECTED MATERIAL TO BE PICKED UP AND DISPOSED OF BY ASHLAND CHEMICAL PERSONNEL.  CAR WAS RELEASED AND FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.

WHILE ROTATING DRUMS IN BACK OF TRUCK, BENCH CAME LOOSE FROM SECURED POSITION & SWUNG AROUND, HIT DRUM IN BACK OF TRACK & KNOCKED IT OFF REAR OF TRUCK.  I IMMEDIATELY GRABBED ABSORBANTS, CONTINUED SPREADING LIQUID & ABSORBANT MATERIAL FROM ASPHALT.

column168: THE EMPTY TRAILER (W/RESIDUE) WAS SPOTTED ON TERMINAL YARD.  AT 21:00 HOURS, A MECHANIC NOTICED A VAPOR RISING FROM THE DOME AREA.  THE SHIPPING PAPERS WERE LOCATED AND THE CHAMBERS WORKS (DU PONT) EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS CONTACTED.  THE "TEAM" REPLACED THE LEAKING PRESSURE GAUGE AND COMPLETED ITS WORK AT 03:20 ON 4/12/93.

WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER FORKLIFT OPERATOR PUNCTURED ONE CARTON CONTAINING FOUR ONE GALLON PLASTIC BOTTLES OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID USED AS A DRIVEWAY CLEANER.  ONLY ONE BOTTLE WAS DAMAGED.  THE ONE DAMAGED BOTTLE WAS USED FOR ITS INTENDED PURPOSE AT OUR TERMINAL.  THE REMAINING SHIPMENT WAS DELIVERED.  DISCUSSED PROPER FORKLIFT PROCEDURES WITH OPERATOR.
DURING TRANSIT THE CHEMICAL IN ONE DRUM WITH A POLY LINER SLOSHED OUT BETWEEN THE LINER AND DRUM.  THE DRUM HAD A SMALL STRESS FRACTURE WHICH ALLOWED A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL TO LEAK OUT.

ONE FIVE GALLON PAIL WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER.  THE PAIL HAD FALLEN IN TRANSIT AND KNOCKED THE LID LOOSE.  APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT OF MATERIAL LEAKED FROM THE PAIL.  TALKED TO PERSONNEL WHO LOADED TRAILER AND ADVISED THEM OF PROPER BLOCKING AND BRACING PROCEDURES.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING DRUMS ONE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING.  APPARENTLY ONE HAD BEEN PUNCTURED BY A NAIL PROTRUDING FROM THE PALLET THEY WHERE LOADED ON. PATCHED DRUM AND SENT ON TO FINAL DESTINATION.
EMPLOYEE WAS LOADING DRUMS WITH FORKLIFT ATTACHMENT AND UPON RELEASING THE DRUM - THE ATTACHMENT STRUCK THE RIB OF DRUM - CAUSING IT TO OPEN.

AS SHIPMENT WAS BEING TRANSPORTED ACROSS THE RAMP, THIS PIECE FELL FROM THE ULD ONTO THE RAMP.  THE PIECE WAS CAUGHT UNDER THE DOLLY AND DRAGGED A SHORT DISTANCE, CAUSING A LEAK TO FORM AT THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.  THE LEAK WAS ABSORBED USING FLOOR DRY.  DRUM AND FLOOR DRY WERE PLACED IN A CONTAINMENT DRUM FOR DISPOSAL.

AS THE ULD IN WHICH THIS SHIPMENT MOVED TO HUB WAS OPENED, IT WAS NOTICED THAT ONE OF THE PIECES WAS SOAKED WITH FLUID.  THE PIECE WAS REMOVED AND OPENED.  ONE OF THE INNER PACKAGINGS BOTTOMS HAD BEEN CRACKED AND HAD LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 2 LITRES OF ITS CONTENTS INTO THE OUTER PACKAGING. THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF ANY FLUID LEAKING OUTSIDE OF THE PACKAGE.  THE DAMAGED PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN A CONTAINMENT DRUM AWAITING WRITTEN AUTHORIZATION FOR ITS DISPOSAL.

DRIVER FOUND ONE DRUM LEAKING UPON ARRIVAL AT THE RECEIVER.  THE DRUM WAS REMOVED AND INSPECTED.  THE DRUM HAD A LEAK IN THE BOTTOM SEAM WHERE THE DRUM BOTTOM IS WELDED ON.  ALL WASTE WAS REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER BY RECEIVER.

THE OTHER VEHICLE HAD STOPPED & DONE SOME BUSINESS AT THE SITE.  THE DRIVER THEN RE-ENTERED THE VEHICLE AND DROVE FORWARD OVER THE WARNING CONE, TIGHTFILL FITTING & HOSE.  DRIVER WAS AT THE TRUCK AND CLOSED THE VALVE IMMEDIATELY THEREBY LIMITING THE PRODUCT SPILLAGE. PRODUCT WAAS CONTAINED ON SITE WITH FLOOR DRY UNTIL FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED AND COMPLETED CLEANUP.

column168: FLT 814 FROM HOUSTON REPORTED STRONG ODORS IN THE COCKPIT.  THE CREW WENT ON PURE OXYGEN AND REQUESTED EMERGENCY SERVICES AT IND.  THE AIRCRAFT (N254FE) WAS ISOLATED IN THE "PENALTY" BOX AT THE IND A/P FACILITY.  CREW REPORTED NO ILL EFFECTS AND LATER RETURNED TO HOUSTON ON RETURN FLIGHT 864.  THE PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED ON ITS SIDE IN THE HAZARDOUS CONTAINER. FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED THE INNER SEAL/PLUG NOT PROPERLY IN PLACE, ALLOWING THE GASOLINE TO ESCAPE.  THE PACKAGE IS BELIEVED TO HAVE SHIFTED IN FLIGHT, CONTRIBUTING TO THE LEAKAGE.  THERE WAS NO EXTERNAL LEAKAGE FROM THE BOX.  PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND THE SHIPPER CONTACTED FOR PACKAGE DISPOSITION.  IND FAA/CAFSO WAS NOTIFIED THE FOLLOWING MORNING.

PACKAGE WAS RUN OVER BY VEHICLE.  INSPECTION DETERMINED INNER RECEPTACLES WERE CRUSHED CAUSING A SMALL AMOUNT OF ADHESIVE TO LEAK.  THE PACKAGE WAS THEN PALCED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.
1 GALLON WAS DENTED IN ON SIDE.  CAP WAS LOOSE AND A VERY SMALL AMOUNT LEAKED OUT.

THE DAMAGED PORTION WAS DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PROCEDURES.  SHIPPER SHOULD BE NOTIFIED REGARDING PACKAGING PROCEDURES.

PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN THE PRIMARY SORT. ONE OF FOUR GALLON JUGS HAD A LOOSE CAP.  THE COMPLETE CONTENTS WAS REPACKAGED AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  THE DAMAGED CARTON WAS DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DISPOSAL PROCEDURE.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING #2 FUELIOIL VIA PUMP-OFF, INTO CONSIGNEE'S STORAGE TANK AT FACILITY LOCATED IN RIDGEWAY, IOWA, THE TANK FILLED UP AND BEGAN OVER FLOWING INTO THE FACILITY'S SECONDARY CONTAINMENT DIKE. THE TRANSPORT DRIVER SAW THE EVENT AND SHUT OFF THE PUMP IMMEDIATELY. DUE TO THE SPRING THAW, THE CONSIGNEES EMPLOYEES INADVERTANTLY LEFT THE PLUG OUT OF THE DRAIN HOLE. THE FUEL ESCAPED FROM THE CONTAINMENT AREA AND ENTERED A STORM WATER IN LET IN THE FORM OF A VERTICAL PERFORATED TILE INLET. AN ESTIMATED QUANTITY OF 319 GALLONS FLOWED THROUGH THE TILE LINE NORTHWARD TO A DRAINAGE DITCH WHERE IT FLOWED TILE LINE NORTHEASTWARD TO TEN MILE CREEK. AT APPROXIMAELY 0700 THE IA DNR UNIT MANCHESTER, IA WAS CALLED AND APPRISED OF THE SITUATION. INITIAL MOP-UP AFFORTS BEGAN AT 0900 WITH CREWS SOAKING UP FUELOIL IN THE FIRST MILE OF FLOW. STRAW BALE FILLERING CONTAIMNENT WAS INSTITUTED AT THE DOUBLE CULVERT WHERE WINNESHIEK CO. RD W-14 CROSSES THE DRAINAGE DITCH, AND ZOO YARDS UPSTREAM FROM THE BRIDGE ON "HAPPY HOLLOW ROAD" WHERE IT CROSS THE TEN MILE CREEK. ON FRIDAY, 04-16-93, CREWS REMOVED THE STRAW BALES, AND THEN PLACED OIL-SOAKING "BOOM" ACROSS THE FLOWAGE IN BOTH LOCATIONS. FUTURE PREVENTION IS ASSURED BY CONSIGNEE KEEPING THE DRAIN PLUG IN PLACE AND LOCKED AFTER NORMAL BUSINESS HOURS. THE CONSIGNEE AND TRANSPORT COMPANY WILL HAVE THE LARGE OIL SOAKING "BOOM" ON HAND FOR ONLY FUTURE SITUATIONS.

DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT CLEAN HARHORS OF CLEVELAND, INC LOCATED IN CLEVELAND, OHIO TWO VAN TRAILERS WERE BACKED UP TO EACH OTHER TO CONDUCT A TRANSFER OF CONTAINERS FROM ONE TRANSPORT VEHICLE TO ANOTHER.  PRIOR TO BACKING THE TRUCKS TO EACH OTHER, THE LOAD LOCK OF ONE VEHICLE WAS REMOVED FROM THE LOAD.  AS THE TRUCK BACKED UP TO THE SECOND VEHICLE, THE TAILGATES STRUCK EACH OTHER JARRING THE LOAD.  ONE 16 GALLON CONTAINER WAS OVERTURNED AS A RESULT OF THIS JARRING ACTION.  AS THE CONTAINER HIT THE TRAILER'S FLOOR, THE LID POPPED OFF AND TWO CONTAINERS THAT HAD BEEN PACKED INSIDE THE CONTAINED BROKE RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 1.5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRANSPORT VEHICLE WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT. PERSONNEL FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF CLEVELAND, INC IMMEDIATELY ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY AND REPACKAGED THE CONTAINER FOR ITS FACILITY.  ALL CLEAN UP MATERIAL WAS CONTAINERIZED AND SENT TO A FULLY LICENSED HAZARDOUS WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY FOR DISPOSAL. THE CONTAINER AND MATERIAL USED TO COLLECT THE RELEASED PRODUCT WERE PROPERLY MANAGED AND DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE DESTINATION FACILITY.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A REOCCURENCE OF THIS SITUATION, THE DRIVER HAS BEEN REINSTRUCTED TO INSURE THAT THE LOAD IS PROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED TO AVOID CONTAINER DAMAGE IN THE EVENT OF AN UNINTENTIONAL LOAD SHIFT DURING TRANSPORTATION.

column168: THE DRIVER WAS PUMPING 1500 GALLONS OF PRODUCT TO CONSIGNEE'S STORAGE TANK THROUGH APPROXIMATELY 80 FEET OF 2 INCH HOSE AND SPLICED TOGETHER IN SEVERAL SECTIONS.  THE FIRST 40 FEET OF HOSE BELONGED TO THE CARRIER AND THE REMAINAING HOSE BELONGED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  APPROXIMATELY TWO THIRDS OF THE 1500 GALONS HAD BEEN PUMPED OFF WHEN A SPLICE IN THE CONSIGNEE'S HOSE CAME APART AND MOST OF THE REMAINING 500 GALLONS DISCHARGED ON TO THE GROUND.  ABOUT HALFWAY THROUGH THE PUMPING PROCESS THE DRIVER CLIMBED IN THE DRIVERS SEAT OF HIS TRACTOR TO CATCH UP ON HIS PAPER WORK AND FAILED TO NOTICE THE HOSE FAILURE.  WHILE THE DRIVER MAY NOT HAVE PREVENTED THE FAILURE OF THE HOSE SPLICE AND THE INEVITABLE "HAZMAT INCIDENT" HE CERTAINLY COULD HAVE BEEN INSTRUMENTAL IN REDUCING THE AMOUNT OF THE SPILL HAD HE HAVE BEEN MORE OBSERVANT DRUING THE PUMPING PROCESS.  I FEEL THAT HE HAD MADE A SERIOUS ERROR IN JUDGEMENT BY ASSUMING THAT BECAUSE THE FIRST HALF OF THE TRANSFER WENT OK THAT ALL WOULD REMAIN WELL.  THIS VERY PROCEDURE WAS JUST COVERED IN A SAFETY SEMINAR FOR OUR DRIVERS ON APRIL 12 OF THIS YEAR.  WHILE THE DRIVER HAS AN EXCELLENT DRIVING RECORD AND HAS ALSO BEEN A VERY GOOD EMPLOYEE FOR OUR COMPANY HE HAS BEEN REPRIMANDED SEVERLY FOR HIS POOR JUDGEMENT AND WILL BE SUBJECT TO POSSIBLE DISCHARGE IN THE EVENT IF A SIMILAR INCIDENT IN THE FURUTE.  IN ADDRESSING THE PROBLEM OF THE FAILED HOSE SPLICE I AM ADVISING OUR DRIVER S THAT IT IS NOT ENOUGH TO JUST CHECK OUR OWN HOSES AND FITTINGS, BUT OUR CUSTOMERS ALSO.  IF THEY FIND A PROBLEM WITH A CUSTOMER'S EQUIPMENT OR PROCEURE THEN ADVISE THE CUSTOMER TO PLEASE REMEDY THE POTENTIAL HAZARD.  IF THE CUSTOMER FAILS TO DO SO THEN THE DRIVER SHOULD CONSULT WITH HIS SUPERVISOR ABOUT THE HAZARD, BUT UNDER NO CIRCUMSTANCES SHOULD HE ATTEMPT TO MAKE THE TRANSFER UNTIL HE IS SATISFIED WITH THE SAFETY OF ALL EQUIPMENT BEING USED.  A HOSE SPLICED WITH THE WRONG SPLICING MATERIAL SHOULD HAVE BEEN UNACCEPTABLE TO OUR DRIVER EVEN IF HE WAS DIRECTED TO HOOK ON TO IT BY THE CONSIGNEE'S EMPLOYEE AND EVEN IF IT HAD BEEN USED BEFORE WITHOUT INCIDENT. ALL OF OUR DRIVERS HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO KEEP THE TRANSFER PROCESS IN SIGHT AND REMAIN PREPARED FOR AN EMERGENCY SHUTDOWN AT ALL TIMES DURING THE TRANSFER.  EMERGENCY PERSONNEL WERE NOTIFIED SHORTLY AFTER THE DISCOVERY OF THE SPILL AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND HAZMAT TEAM ARRIVED SHORTLY AFTERWARDS.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED TO THE IMMEDIATE AREA WITH SAFETY SOCKS, (THESE ARE CARRIED ON ALL OF OUR TRACTORS) AND SAND APPLIED TO THE SURFACE OF THE SPILL.  THERE WAS NO RUN OFF TO PUBLIC LAND OR WATERS.  THIS PRODUCT IS VERY THICK AND SETS UP QUICKLY WHEN EXPOSED TO AIR.  THIS HELPS TO LIMIT THE SPREAD AS COMPARED TO A LOW VISCOSITY PRODUCT.  THE PRODUCT WAS SHOVELED UP AND PLACED IN 55 GALLON DRUMS FOR LATER DISPOSITION.

THE DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE AIRPORT AT APPROX. 15:20, WITH 7500 GALLONS OF JET FUEL.  UPON ARRIVING THE DRIVER HAD TO WAIT FOR LYNCH PERSONNEL TO INSPECT THE FUEL.  WHILE WAITING HE GOT A FUEL TANK PRINT OUT THAT INDICATED THAT TANK #3 WOULD HOLD 1382 GALLONS OF FUEL.  HE FILLED THIS TANK TO THE 90" MARK ON THE GUAGE STICK AND PUT THE REMAINDER OF THE LOAD IN TANK #5, WHICH SHOULD HAVE HELD THE REMAINDER OF THE LOAD, WHICH WAS APPROXIMATELY 6300 GALLONS.  WHEN HE WENT TO CHECK ON OPERATIONS HE DISCOVERED FUEL OVERFLOWING OUT OF THE BREATHER PIPE.  HE IMMEDIATELY SHUT THE PUMP DOWN AND CALLED CFR.  IN THE FUTURE THE 30,000 GALLON TANK WILL ONLY BE FILLED TO THE 25,000 MARK AND THE 10,000 GALLON TANK WILL ONLY BE FILLED TO THE 9,000 MARK.

column168: OUR VEHICLE WAS TRANSPORTING A CONTAINERIZED SHIPMENT FROM THE SEALAND SERVICES, LONG BEACH, CA FACILITY TO THE SEALAND SERIVES, OAKLAND, CA PORT. THE CONTAINER WAS A SEALED EXPORT LOAD TENDERED TO CSX INTERMODAL AS AN "FAK" (FREIGHT ALL KINGS) SHIPMENT, WITH NO PAPERWORK OR PLACARDS ON THE CONTAINER.  PRIOR TO DEPATURE FROM LONG BEACH, OUR DRIVER VERIFIED WITH THE SEALAND GATE CLERK ABOUT THE CONTENTS OF THE LOAD AND WAS ASSURED THAT THERE WERE NO HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  ENROUTE TO THE FINAL DESTINATION, OUR UNIT ALLEGEDLY SWERVED TO AVOID A VEHICLE THAT CUT IN FRONT.  OUR UNIT TURNED ON TO THE SHOULDER AND OVERTURNED.  AFTER THE OVERTURNED UNIT WAS INSPECTED, IT BECAME APPARENT THAT THERE WERE MATERIALS LEAKING.  UPON CONTACT WITH SEALAND SERVICES IN LONG BEACH, THEY FAXED US THE SHIPPING PAPERS THAT INDICATED THERE WERE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS IN THE CONTAINER. THE LOAD WAS UPRIGHTED AND MOVED UNDER SUPERVISION TO ANOTHER SITE FOR THE CLEANUP.

THE NORMAL VIBRATION OF THE TRAILER DURING TRANSIT CAUSED THE GLASS TO CRACK AND LEAK THRU THE BOX ONTO TRAILER FLOOR.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED AND DISPOSED OF BY ARISTECH'S IN PLANT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONSE TEAM.  (THIS IS WHY WE DON'T HAVE PACKAGE MARKING INFORMATION).  THIS SPILL COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED BY STRONGER PACKAGING AND NOT LOADING IT ON THE TAIL OF THE TRAILER WHERE THE MOST VIBRATION OCCURS.

BOX WAS WET WHEN REMOVED FROM TRAILER.  THIS NOTICED BY DOCKWORKER. DOCKWORKER LEFT BOX AND WENT TO GET ABSORBANT MATERIAL AND OVERPACK. WHILE HE WAS LEAVING A SKID THAT WAS PROPPED UP NEXT TO IT FELL OVER ONTO THE BOX AND CRUSHED TWO OF THE GLASS BOTTLES THAT WERE ALREADY LEAKING. SPILL WAS CONTAINED, AND CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT.  WASTE WAS PLACED INTO AN AIR TIGHT OVERPACK ARRANGEMENTS HAVE BEEN MADE WITH SAMSEL SERVICES COMPANY IN CLEVELAND OHIO FOR WASTE DISPOSAL.  THIS SPILL COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED BY BETTER PACKAGING FROM THE SHIPPER AND LESS HUMAN ERROR ON THE PART OF OUR DOCKWORKER WHEN PROTECTING THE SCENE.

A DOCKWORKER RAMMED TWO MOTOR FORK INTO DRUM WHEN LOADING TRAILER.  DRUM WAS THEN FLIPPED ONTO ITS SIDE TO STOP LEAK. SPILL WAS ABSORBED WITH OIL DRY AND DAMAGED DRUM WAS PATCHED AND OVERPACKED INTO A DOT SALVAGE DRUM. THE WASTE WAS SWEPT UP AND PLACED INTO A SEPERATE PAIL.  THE SHIPPER TOOK BOTH THE WASTE MATERIAL AND THE GOOD MATERIAL BACK TO SALVAGE.  THE DOCKWORKER THAT WAS CARELESS IN THIS MATTER IS NOW BE DECERTIFIED AS A FORKLIFT OPERATOR UNTIL HE CAN PROVE HE HAS LEARNED TO VIEW HAZARDOUS MATERIAL IN A MORE CAREFUL MANNER.

THIS DELIVERY SITE WAS UNDER CONSTRUCTION FOR A DIKE WALL AT THE UNLOADING AREA.  THERE WERE TWO (ALLEGHENY LUDLUM) EMPLOYEES WORKING AT THIS PARTICULAR SITE.  THE WORKERS HAD TO WAIT FOR THE DELIVERY TO BE MADE, BEFORE CONTINUING THEIR OPERATION.  I OPENED THE PLUG ON (ALLEGHENY'S) FILL PIPE AND APPROXIMATELY EIGHT (8) OUNCES OF PRODUCT RAN ONTO THE GROUND I HOOKED UP THE FITTINGS AND BLEW THE PRODUCT INTO THEIR TANK. WHEN HOSE WENT EMPTY I CLOSED ALL VALVES, AND AT THAT TIME I UNHOOKED THE HOSES.  I TOOK SPECIAL CARE NOT TO ALLOW ANY PRODUCT IN THE BUCKET.  THE WORKERS THANKED ME, I THEN ASKED TO (ALLEGHENY'S) EMPLOYEES WHERE I SHOULD RINSE OUT THE HOSES TO PREVENT ANY PRODUCT LEAKING ON THE TRIP HOME.  I WAS TOLD TO PUT THE PRODUCT INTO THE DRAIN INSIDE DOOR 104.  THERE WERE OIL SUBSTANCES AND ALSO LEAKAGE FROM THEIR (C-10) PUMP IN THIS AREA.  I RINSED THE PRODUCT INTO THE DRAIN (I WAS TOLD THIS WENT TO WATER TREATMENT). ALLEGHENY LUDLUM SHOULD HAVE A SYSTEM TO CATCH ANY SPILLAGE OF PRODUCT DURING UNLOADING PROCEDURES AND THERE MUST BE A PLACE FOR CLEANING HOSES TO ELIMINATE ANY PRODUCT LEAKING WHILE IN TRANSIT. column42: HAZARDOUS WASTE, LIQUID OR SOLID, N.O.S.
column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Water Damage
column168: A CUBIC YARD DOT E-9920 FIBER BOX WAS LOADED WITH WHAT WAS OBSERVED TO BE A DRY METAL HYDROXIDE SLUDGE WASTE.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE DESTINATION FACILITY IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT RESIDUAL LIQUID THAT WAS NOT VISIBLE AT THE TIME OF LOADING, SEPARATED FROM THE MATERIAL CAUSING THE FIBER BOX TO SPLIT OPEN ALONG THE BOTTOM SEAM.  APPROXIMATELY 10 POUNDS OF MATERIAL ESCAPED FROM THE BOTTOM SEAM OF THE CONTAINER ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  A FIELD SERVICE CREW FROM THE DESTINATION FACILITY RECONTAINERIZED THE MATERIAL AND DECONTAMINATED THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER.  THE RECONTAINERIZED MATERIAL ALONG WITH THE SPILL DEBRIS WAS DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE MANIFEST. IN ORDER TO PREVENT A REOCCURRENCE OF THIS SITUATION, ALL PERSONNEL RESPONSIBLE FOR LOADING THIS TYPE OF CONTAINER WILL BE REQUIRED TO INSPECT THE LOAD FOR ANY EVIDENCE OF RESIDUAL LIQUID.  IN THE EVENT RESIUDAL LIQUID IS FOUND OR SUSPECTED, THE MATERIAL IS TO BE RECONTAINERIZED INTO SUITABLE CONTAINERS PRIOR TO TRANSPORTATION.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS EN ROUTE FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC. LOCATED IN BRAINTREE MASSACHUSETTS TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CLEVELAND, INC LOCATED IN CLEVELAND, OHIO.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE DESTINATION FACILITY, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A PINHOLE LEAK WAS DEVELOPED ON THE SIDE OF THE CONTAINER THAT CAUSED APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS OF MATERIAL TO LEAK ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER AND THE CONCRETE SAMPLING PAD ON WHICH THE TRAILER WAS PARKED.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY OVERPACKED THE CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE CONTAINER IS UTILIZED FOR THE MATERIAL BEING OFFERED FOR SHIPMENT.

CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC WAS DISPATCHED TO NARRAGANSETT ELECTRIC LOCATED IN PROVIDENCE, RHODE ISLAND TO PICK UP A LOAD OF WASTEWATER BRING SHIPPED FOR DISPOSAL.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THIS SITE, THE VEHICLE OPERATOR PREPARED THE VEHICLE TO BEGIN THE PROCESS OF LOADING HIS VEHICLE.  AT THIS POINT, THE VEHICLE OPERATOR ENGAGED THE VACUUM UNIT ON THE TANK AND OBSERVED APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS OF RESIDUAL MATERIAL, THAT WAS PRESUMED TO BE FROM THE PREVIOUS LOAD, ESCAPE FROM THE SCRUBBER UNIT ONTO THE GROUND.  THE UNIT WAS IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN AND THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE OWNER OF THE PROPERTY OF THE RELEASE AS WELL AS HIS HOME OFFICE.  THE HOME OFFICE, IN TURN, NOTIFIED THE RHODE ISLAND DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT.  PLEASE NOTE THAT THE RELEASE OCCURRED ON THE PROPERTY OF NARRAGANSETT ELECTRIC BUT THAT THEY WERE IN NO WAY RESPONSIBLE FOR THIS RELEASE.  THE VEHICLE BEING USED AT THIS SITE HAD BEEN DECONTAMINATED PRIOR TO DISPATCH.  UNDER NORMAL CONDITIONS, PRODUCT CONTAINED IN THE TANK IS PREVENTED FROM ENTERING THE SCRUBBER UNIT BY MEANS OF A BUTTERFLY VALVE.  IT APPEARS THAT THIS WAS OPEN DURING TRANSPORTATION OF THE PREVIOUS LOAD RESULTING IN THE MATERIAL ENTERING THE SCRUBBER UNIT.  A CREW WAS DISPATCHED FOR CLEAN HARBOR'S RHODE ISLAND SERVICE CENTER TO CLEAN UP THE RELEASE.  AT THE DIRECTION OF THE STATE OF RHODE ISLAND, THE AREA WHERE THE RELEASE OCCURRED WAS TREATED WITH SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION ADN THE CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS CONTAINERIZED AND SHIPPED TO A FULLY LICENSED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY FOR DISPOSAL. SAMPLES WERE TAKEN FROM THE SPILL AREA TO INSURE THAT ALL CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS REMOVED.  THE RESULTS FROM THE ANALYTICAL INDICATED THAT RESIDUAL CYANIDES WERE NOT DETECTED AT THE CONCLUSION OF THE RESPONSE.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A REOCCURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT, BOTH DRIVERS AND PERSONNEL INVOLVED IN THE CLEANING OF TANK VEHICLES HAVE BEEN REINSTRUCTED TO INSPECT THE SCRUBBER UNITS FOR CONTAMINATION PRIOR TO DISPATCH.  IF MATERIAL IS FOUND IN THE SCRUBBER UNIT, IT IS T BE PROPERLY CLEANED AND PURGED PRIOR TO BEING PUT INTO SERVICE.

WHILE INSPECTING INBOUND TRAIN, THE CAR INSPECTOR DISCOVERED GATX 21198, LOAD OF DENATURED ALCOHOL, LEAKING AT THE RATE OF ABOUT ONE DROP EVERY TEN SECONDS.  THE CAR INSPECTOR REPORTED THE LEAK TO THE YARDMASTER WHO IN TURN NOTIFIED THE LOCAL RAILROAD HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONDER.  AFTER TIGHTENING THE TOP-OPERATED BOTTOM-OUTLET VALVE AND PACKING-GLAND NUT, THE BOTTOM-OUTLET CAP WAS TIGHTENED.  THESE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS STOPPED THE LEAKING.  THE CAR WAS SUBSEQUENTLY RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.

RICK SORRELL OF U.P.R.R. CALLED MONTANA SULPHUR & CHEMICAL CO. AT 1:30 PM ON 4/15/93.  AN ODOR OF H2S WAS COMING FROM THE TOP OF GATX-62147, WHICH WAS RETURNING FROM A CUSTOMER PLANT.  AFTER CONVERSATION WITH RICK, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE LEAK WAS VERY SMALL AND THAT THE CAR SHOULD BE ISOLATED UNTIL A CREW FROM MONTANA SULPHUR & CHEMICAL CO. COULD INSPECT THE SUSPECTED LEAK.    UPON ARRIVAL AT THE U.P.R.R. IN POCATELLO, IDAHO AT 11:00 PM 4/15/93; MYSELF AND DAVE YARLOTT WERE DIRECTED BY RUSS CAMPBELL TO GATX-62147.  I COULD NOT DETECT ANY LEAKAGE AT GROUND LEVEL AROUND THE CAR.  AT THE TOP OF THE CAR, INSIDE THE DOME, A TRACE LEAKAGE WAS COMING FROM THE VALVE PACKING ON THE STEM OF A LOADING VALVE.  SUCH LEAKAGE IS NORMALLY CONTAINED COMPLETELY BY A STEM-SAFETY-CAP ASSEMBLY ATTACHED TO THE MAIN VALVE.  THIS STEM-SAFETY-CAP IS EQUIPPED WITH A SCHRADER VENTING VALVE AND A PRESSURE-TIGHT SCREW-ON CAP TO ALLOW PRESSURE EQUALIZATION BEFORE THE STEM-SAFETY-CAP IS REMOVED.  IN THIS CASE, THE SCREW-ON CAP WAS LOOSE AND WAS SEEPING SLIGHTLY.  TIGHTENING THE CAP WITH MY FINGERS THE LEAK WAS COMPLETELY SEALED.  AS A PRECAUTION, WE REMOVED THE OLD STEM-SAFETY-CAP ASSEMBLY AND REPLACED IT WITH A DIFFERENT ONE.  THIS ONE ALSO DID NOT LEAK, AND THE CAR WAS SAFE FOR TRANSPORT.

column168: D.W. ALM MANAGER CTS WAS NOTIFIED THAT TANKCAR PSPX 12 WAS LEAKING AT MILPITAS, CA.  OH MATERIALS WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED AS WELL AS UP SPECIAL AGENT/HAZMAT BARRY BALLANCE.  CONSIGNEE CHEMCENTRAL WAS ALSO NOTIFIED AND THEY SENT A RESPONSE TEAM FROM THEIR FACILITY.  AT 1500 HRS CHEMCENTRAL RESPONSE TEAM MEMBERS DECIDED TO TRANSLOAD THE TANK CAR DUE TO A LEAK IN THE NIPPLE BETWEEN THE BOTTOM BALL VALVE AND THE TANK CAR.  AT 1830 HRS THE OFFLOADING OF THE TANK INTO OVER THE ROAD TRUCKS WAS COMPLETED.  TANK WAS FORWARDED TO EASTMAN CHEMICAL PRODUCTS FOR REPAIR. MANAGER ALM ADVISED CHEMTREC AT 1225 HRS.

ON 040293 AT APPROXIMATELY 130 AM A CARMAN WAS INSPECTING AN INBOUND TRAIN IN TRACK R1, SETTEGAST YARD, HOUSTON, TX.  HE OBSERVED A VAPOR CLOUD AND FOUND THE ABOVE CAR LEAKING.  MTO PENNINGTON WAS NOTIFIED AND MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY (MCTS) REEDER WAS NOTIFIED.  MCTS REEDER RESPONDED, CAR WAS LEAKING A STEADY STREAM FROM THE SUMP.  REEDER CALLED THE HOUSTON FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TEAM, CHEMTREC, AND MONSANTO.  THE LEAK WAS STOPPED AT 505 AM.  MONSANTO RESPRESENTATIVES RENFRO AND BREWER ARRIVED AT 630 AM.  THEY HIRED OHM CORP. TO TRANSFER THE LOAD AND REMEDIATE THE ENVIRONMENT.  THE OHM TEAM ARRIVED AT 7 AM. MONSANTO AND OHM ASKED THE HOUSTON HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TEAM TO STANDBY IN CASE OF EMERGENCY.  DUE TO POOR COMMUNICATIONS AND A SERIES OF COMMUNICATION FAILURES THE TRANSFER DID NOT BEGIN UNTILL 2 PM.  THE PUMP HAD BEEN RUNNING ABOUT FIVE MINUTES WHEN THE PATCH ON THE CAR FAILED.  THE LEAK WAS STOPPED AGAIN BY THE HOUSTON HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TEAM.  ACID FOAM WAS USED TO SUPRESS VAPORS.  LIME WAS USED TO NEUTRALIZE THE SPILLED MATERIAL.  A TOTAL OF 19,211 GALLONS WERE TRANSFERRED FROM THE CAR. 19,500 GALLONS WERE ORIGINALLY LOADED FROM THE CAR.  19,500 GALLONS WERE ORIGINALLY LOADED IN THE CAR, MAKING THE SPILL APPROXIMATLEY 289 GALLONS. THE OPERATION WAS COMPLETED AT APPROXIMATLEY 12 MIDNIGHT.

ON 04-11-93, 1000 HOURS, SPECIAL AGENT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEAN WOMACK WAS CONTACTED BY SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT JAY PLUMMER.  PLUMMER INFORMED WOMACK THAT YRAD PERSONNEL HAD SMELLED AN ODOR OF AMMONIA COMING FROM TANK CAR WGFX 205.  CAR WAS ISOLATED TO THE WEST END OF REISOR YARD. FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED A SMALL VAPOR LEAK ESCAPING FROM AROUND THE RETAINER PACKING OF THE "B" END, LIQUID VALVE HANDLE.  WOMACK TIGHTENED THE PACKAGING RETAINER BOLTS AND THE LEAK WAS SECURED.  PROTECTIVE HOUSING WAS SECURED WITH SEAL "M.P.R.R.  23-186409". WOMACK MADE NOTIFICATIONS TO CHEMTREC, SPEAKING WITH J. LONG, LOUISIANA STATE POLICE AND LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY.

column168: MGR. CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY REEDER RECEIVED A CALL FROM MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS R. PENNINGTON THAT THE ABOVE CAR WAS SLOSHING LIQUID FROM THE TOP WHEN IT WA MOVED.  REEDER RESPONDED AND FOUND THE TOP OF THE CAR WET WITH SPILLED ALKALI.  SEAL CHEVRON 211113 WAS REMOVED FROM THE MANWAY COVER PLATE.  THERE WAS NO GASKET UDER THE COVER.  REEDER MADE A NEW GAKSET FROM GORE TEX MATERIAL, CLOSED AND BOLTED THE COVER.  THE CAR WAS RESEALED WITH MPRR 17 169075.  AS HE WAS LEAVING THE SCENE, REEDER RECEIVED ANOTHER CALL FROM PENNINGTON.  HE HAD JUST RECEIVED A CALL FROM H.A. HAIRRELL WHO WAS THE ENGINEER ON THE JOB THAT HAD FOUND THE LEAKING CAR.  HE REPORTED THE SKIN ON HIS FACE WAS RED AND BURNING.  THIS WAS APPARENTLY CAUSED BY AN EXPOSURE TO THE MIST.  FIRST AID WAS ADMINISTERED AND HE DID NOT THINK MEDICAL TREATMENT WAS NECESSARY AT THAT TIME.  MCTS REEDER NOTIFIED CHEMTREC.  RUSS WHITE, TOXICOLOGIST (CHEVRON), NOTIFIED MGR. REEDER AND ADVISED THAT MR. HAIRRELL HAD RECEIVED PROPER FIRST AID TREATMENT.

ALSO, PLUG IN THE GAUGING TUBE VALVE WAS NOT WRENCH TIGHT.  REEDER TIGHTENED BOTH FITTINGS.  THE CAR RESEALED WITH MPRR 17 169083.  CAR WAS RELEASED FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT. WHILE CONDUCTING ROUTINE TANK CAR INSPECTIONS, MGR CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATIONS SAFETY (MCTS) G. REEDER NOTED CAR GATX 11644 WAS LEAKING WHEN THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING WAS OPENED.  THE WEATHER HOOD WAS MISSING FROM THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE.  THE VALVE WAS MAKING A SLIGHT HISSING SOUND. REEDER WORKED WITH THE VALVE BUT WAS UNABLE TO STOP THE LEAK.  DUE TO THE SMALL NATURE OF THE LEAK, IT WAS UNDETECTABLE WITHOUT OPENING THE HOUSING. CAR WAS ALLOWED TO MOVE TO DESTINATION FOR REPAIR.  DESTINATION WAS FREEPORT, TX WHICH IS A SHORT DISTANCE FROM WHERE THE LEAK WAS DISCOVERED. CHEMTREC AND JOE STEFOANON AT BASF WERE CONTACTED AND ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE FOR THE CAR TO BE INSPECTED AND REPAIRED.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails); Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: THE TRUCK DRIVER JOHN MOROSKO, TRAILER #472 ARRIVED AT THE JC PENNEY'S STORE IN ATHENS, OHIO OPENED THE TRAILER DOOR TO MAKE A DELIVERY AND DISCOVERED A SMALL LEAK IN A DRUM LOADED ON THE REAR TO TRAILER.  THE DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY LAYED DOWN AND BLOCKED.  THIS STOPPED THE LEAK. INVESTIGATION SHOWED THE DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY A SMALL NAIL PENETRATING THE DRUM NEAR THE BOTTOM.  THE NAIL WAS IN THE PIECE OF TIMBER USED FOR BLOCKING.  THE CONSIGNEE WAS CONTACTED FROM THE ZANESVILLE, OHIO TERMINAL OF PUTNAM TRANSFER.  THE CONSIGNEE STATED THE SHIPENT WOULD NOT BE ACCEPTED BECAUSE OF THE PUNCTURED DRUM.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED WITH THE HELP OF JOE DEBNAM AT CHEMTREC # 1(800) 424-9300.  THE SHIPPER LINDA, ADVISED TO RETURN THE DRUM TO THE ZANESVILLE TERMINAL, PUT IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND SHIP IT BACK TO NORTHERN CHEMICAL, 360 LITERARY ROAD, CLEVELAND, OHIO.  THIS WAS DONE.  THE SPILLED AMOUNT HAD SOAKED INTO THE BOARDS, BUT IT WAS COVERED WITH A SMALL AMOUNT OF KITTY LITER.  THE SHIPPER ADVISED TO WASH OUT THE TRAILER USING LOTS OF WHITE VINEGAR.  THE TRAILER WAS WASHED OUT BY THE GARAGE AT THE ZANESVILLE TERMINAL.  THIS DRUM HAD BEEN LOADED AT THE ZANESVILLE, OHIO TERMINAL ONTO TRAILER 472 FOR DELIVERY.

BENNY MAHAFFEY'S STATEMENT:  THE DRUM FELL OFF THE PALLET AND WHEN IT STRUCK THE FLOOR THE TOP CAME OFF DRUM, SPILLING 50 GALLONS OF LIQUID.  I CALLED MR. TERRY FOSTER WHO IN TURN GOT IN TOUGH WITH DHEC.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: DURING THE COURSE OF A ROUTINE INSPECTION, SPL AGENT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DECHANT NOTED APPARENT PRODUCT RESIDUE ON THE TOP AND SIDES OF RAILCAR. RESIDUE ON SIDES HAD DRIED AND CRYSTALLIZED; MATERIAL ON TOP WAS PARTIALLY DRY, WITH SOME STILL WET.  FURTHER INSPECTION DISCLOSED QUICK OPENING FILL HOLE WAS COMPLETELY UNCOVERED; COVER WAS DISENGAGED AND POSITIONED 180 DEGREES FROM OPENING WITH NO GASKET FOUND.  LOAD WAS VISIBLE, WITH A FOAMY CONSISTENCY APPARENT ON THE TOP OF THE LIQUID; LIQUID LEVEL WAS APPROXIMATELY 3 FEET BELOW OUTAGE GAUGE BAR.  ADDITIONAL INSPECTION DISCLOSED CONSIDERABLE DETERIORATION ON ALL FITTINGS IN THE MANWAY AREA. NUMEROUS HOLES WERE VISIBLE IN THE RUBBER LINING, WITH CORROSION APPARENT BENEATH THE LINING.  GASKETING BETWEEN THE MANWAY COVER PLATE, NOZZLE AN SEGMENTAL WASHERS WAS VISIBLY CRACKED AND WAS BRITTLE TO THE TOUCH.  FILL HOLE LOCKBAR WAS PITTED AND HEAVILY CORRODED AND WASHERS USED AS SPACERS ON THE FILL HOLE EYEBOLT HAD CORRODED TO APPROXIMATELY 50% OF THEIR ORIGINAL THICKNESS.  EYEBOLT THREADS WERE CORRODED TO THE POINT THAT ASSEMBLY WAS INOPERABLE.  THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY COVER WAS CRACKED IN TWO PLACES, WITH ONE CRACK EXTENDING THROUGH 1 3/4 INCHES OF THE 2-INCH PLATE THICHNESS.  ONE EXTERIOR SAFETY APPLIANCE DEFECT WAS ALSO NOTED; ONE RUNG ON THE SIDE LADDER, RIGHT SIDE, BROKE FREE WHEN STEPPED ON DURING THE INSPECTION.  THE RIVET SECURING THE RUNG WAS FOUND BROKEN IN HALF, WITH OVER 1/2 THE THICKNESS OF THE RIVET CORRODED AWAY.  THIS RIVET WAS REPLACED WITH A 5/8" X 2" BOLT IMMEDIATELY, TO ALLOW SAFE REPAIR ACCESS. TO THE EXTENT POSSIBLE, FILL HOLE COVER WAS PROTECTED, CAR BAD ORDERED AND TRACK BLUE FLAGGED UNTIL PROPER REPAIRS COULD BE MADE, WITH SHIPPERS RECOMMENDATIONS, THE FOLLOWING MORNING.  SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED VIA CHEMTREC, AND AUTHORIZED REPAIRS USING RUBBER OR PLASTIC FILLER MATERIALS AS NECESSARY.  ON 4/21/93 DECHANT CLEANED EYEBOLT SUFFICIENTLY TO ALLOW USE OF ADDITIONAL FILLER TO SECURE, INSTALLED BLACK RUBBER GASKET AND TIGHTENED ALL FITTINGS TO THE EXTENT NECESSARY TO ALLOW MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.  CONSIGNEE WAS ADVISED OF THE CONDITION OF THE RAILCAR PRIOR TO RELEASE.  CAR WAS CLEARED FOR MOVEMENT 1455 HRS 4/22/93 AND BLUE FLAG PROTECTION REMOVED.  SHIPPER WILL INSPECT CAR PRIOR TO FUTURE LOADING.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Water Damage
column168: D.C. COOPER, MANAGER, CTS, WAS NOTIFIED BY THE UNION PACIFIC MOTOR FREIGHT RAMP SUPERVISOR, MR. WARREN WYRICK, THAT BIN NUMBER RSCU 26, CONTANING A HAZARDOUS WASTE, WAS NOTED LEAKING IN THE UPMF FACILITY, STOCKTON, CALIFORNIA.  THE ROLLOFF BIN HAD BEEN LOADED ONTO A FLATCAR, TTWX 979019, FOR MOVEMENT ON AN EASTBOUND TRAIN WHEN IT WAS OBSERVED DRIPPING A LIGHT COLORED LIQUID FROM THE BOTTOM AREA OF THE END CLOSURE.  STOCKTON FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD CLOSED DOWN THE RAMP OPERATIONS UNTIL THE INCIDENT WAS EVALUATED.  ONCE THEY DETERMINED THE PROBLEM WAS MINIMAL, THEY ALLOWED THE RAMP TO REOPEN.  OHM WAS CALLED BY UNION PACIFIC TO RESPOND AND MITIGATE THE INCIDENT.  UPON THEIR ARRIVAL, THEY WERE MET BY REPRESENTATIVES OF GREAT WESTERN CHEMICAL, WHO WERE ALSO RESPONDING, AS THE ORIGINAL SHIPPER WAS ONE OF THEIR CUSTOMERS.  INSPECTION OF THE BIN DEVELOPED THE END CLOSURE WAS ALLOWING PRODUCT TO SEEP BY AND IN THE PROCESS OF TIGHTENING THE CHAIN, THE WELD HOLDING THE CHAIN BROKE.  THE BIN WAS THEN REMOVED FROM THE FLATCAR BY UPMF AND PLACED ONTO PLASTIC SHEETING, WITH THE CLOSURE END ELEVATED BY BLOCK, WHICH VIRTUALLY STOPPED THE LEAK, THE CHAIN WAS WELDED BACK IN PLACE THE FOLLOWING MORNING AND THE END CLOSURE PROPERLY SECURED.  THE FLATCAR AS CLEANED , THE RESIDUE PLACED INTO OVERPACKS AND THE BIN WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.

THE SHIPMENT WAS CLEANED UP BY CONTAINERIZED CHEMICAL AND DISPOSED OF BY THEM.

THE LEAKING SHIPMENT WAS FOUND UPON UNLOADING OFF OF THE FLIGHT.  THE SPILL WAS BROUGHT TO THE ATTENTION OF LEON SAMPER, WHO NOTIFIED THE ENVIRONMENTAL AFFAIRS DEPARTMENT.  THEY INSTRUCTED THE OPERATIONS MGR. DOUG BRELAND TO CALL A LOCAL DISPOSAL COMPANY TO CONDUCT THE CLEAN UP.  CLIFF BERRY, INC WAS CONTACTED AND CONDUCTED THE CLEAN UP.  WASTE WAS TAKEN AWAY TO BE DISPOSED OF .  DOUG BRELAND OPS MGR. MIAMI GATEWAY.

D.W. ALM, MANAGER CTS WAS NOTIFIED THAT TRAILER APLU 454965 WAS LEAKING AT THE UP TRAILER FACILITY, OAKLAND, CA.  UP RAMP SUPERVISOR DENT AVERY CONTACTED THE OAKLAND FIRE DEPT. AS WELL AS MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL FOR CLEANUP.  MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL INSPECTED THE LEAKING TRAILER AT 1800 HRS AND DETERMINED THE TRAILER NEEDED TO BE RELOADED DUE TO THE IMPROPER LOADING AND BRACING.  THE TRAILER WAS MOVED TO A SECURE AREA AND ON 4/29/93 RELOADING AND OVERPACKING BEGAN.  1 55 GAL DRUM OF FLAMMABLE LIQUID WHICH WAS LOADED IN THE MIDDLE OF THE TRAILER WAS OVERPACKED AND 6 CASES OF QUART CANS OF MOBIL II OIL WERE OVERPACKED DUE TO LEAKAGE.  THE ENTIRE TRAILER WAS NOT PROPERLY LOADED SUCH AS A PALLET OF WELDING ROD WEIGHING IN EXCESS OF 2880 LBS ON TOP OF ONE OF THE PALLETS OF MOTOR OIL. ON 4/29/93 MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL FINISHED RELOADING TRAILER APLU 454965 AND IT WAS RELEASED TO AMERICAN PRESIDENT LINES.  OAKLAND FIRE DEPT., CAL. OES, AND CHEMTREC WERE ALL NOTIFIED.

D.W. ALM, MANAGER CTS WAS NOTIFIED AT BY UPRR DISPATCHER DUANE LEE THAT TANK CAR GATX 15824 IN OROVILLE, CA WAS VENTING. A HIGH PITCHED SCREAM WAS COMING FROM THE CAR AS WELL AS WHITE VAPOR.  WHILE ENROUTE MGR ALM CONTACTED ALL APPROPRIATE AGENCIES AND REQUESTED A REPRESENTATIVE FROM LIQUID AIR PRODUCT MEET HIM AT THE RAILYARD TO EXAMINE THE TANK CAR OF CARBON DIOXIDE.  UPON ARRIVAL THE CAR WAS EXAMINED AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE 440 PSI RUPTURE DISK WAS BLOWN.  DECISION WAS MADE THAT THE 440 PSI RUPTURE DISK WAS BLOWN.  DECISION  WAS MADE THAT TO STOP THE VENTING WOULD BE DANAGEROUS, THEREFORE THE TANK WAS ALLOWED TO VENT.  TANK MOVED TO THE EAST SIDE OF THE YARD AND IT REMAINED THERE UNTILL IT STOPPED VENTING AT 0230 HRS 4/2/93.  CAL ORO SECURITY COMPANY WAS ENLISTED BY LIQUID AIR AND MONITORED TANK CAR UNTIL SYSTEM DEPLETED.

column168: ON 4-28-93 AT APPROXIMATELY 02:16, P/T SORTER, LAWSON LONG, REPORTED A SPILL IN PRIMARY B OF OUR SORT FACILITY. column168: THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE FAILED ON OUR CARGO TANK TRUCK CAUSING A LEAK AND NITRIC ACID TO FUME.  SOMERSET VOLUNTEER FIRE DEPT EVACUATED RESIDENCES AND OUR DRIVER, GARY LLOYD, WAS TAKEN TO HOSPITAL DUE TO INHALATION OF FUMES.  FIRE COMPANY SUPPLIED A STAINLESS STEEL PLUG RELIEF VALVE OPENING THEN DECONED THE TRAILER AND MOVED IT TO ISOALTED AREA OF RT. 219.  SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY FIRE DEPT.  LACYS SAFETY AND MAINTENANCE COORDINATOR AND MECHANIC WENT TO SCENE WITH NEW PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE AND MADE THE NECESSARY REPAIRS.  GARY LLOYD WAS DISCHARGED FROM HOSPITAL AFTER OBSERVATION AND DECONTAMINATION.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: ON 04-30-93 AT APPROXIMATELY 00:24 GROUND SORT LEAD DON LYNCH REPORTED A SPILL TO HAZMAT DISPATCH.  HE REPORTED THE SPILL AS FOLLOWS: IN C BUILDING ENTER DOOR C-45 EXCEPTION AREA, A CLEAR LIQUID, ODOR OF VINEGAR, NO EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT.  00:30 - HAZMAT COORDINATOR FRAN VANCE AND P/T HAZMAT SPILL SPECIALIST MARK GRIFFITH RESPONDED TO THE SPILL.  UPON ARRIVAL, WE NOTICED SEVERAL WET FIBERBOARD BOXES IN A RED C CONTAINER OMITTING A SLIGHT ODOR OF VINEGAR.  WE PH'D THE LIQUID, FOUND THE READING TO BE NEUTRAL AND PROCEEDED TO CHECK THE BOXES FOR THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK. WE OPENED A LARGE FIBERBOARD BOX AND THE ODOR BECAME VERY STRONG.  WE EGRESSED AND DONNED CARTRIDGE MASKS, THEN CONTINUED OUR INVESTIGATION.  WE PH'D LIQUID ON THE INSIDE OF THE BOX AND ON THE CONTENTS AGAIN FOUND A NEUTRAL READING.  WE FOUND INSIDE THIS BOX SEVERAL NON AEROSOL SPRAY TYPE PLASTIC BOTTLES, A HAND PUMP TYPE SPRAYER, A COUPLE OF GALLON SIZE PLASTIC BOTTLES AND A SMALL 14 OUNCE PLASTIC BOTTLE.  ALL OF THESE FOUND A READING OF 0 FROM THE LIQUID IN THE 14 OUNCE BOTTLE.  WE CLOSED THE BOX AND PLACED IT INTO A PLASTIC BAG. WE PLACED THE OTHER BOXES THAT WERE WET INTO INDIVIDUAL PLASTIC BAGS AND TRANSPORTED THEM TO THE HAZMAT SORT BUILDING FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION AND NEUTRALIZATION.  00:51 - CLEAR OF C-45 EXCEPTION AREA.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE HAZMAT SORT BUILDING, I ENLISTED THE HELP OF TWO ADDITIONAL P/T HAZMAT SPILL SPECIALIST, RANDY WILLIAMS AND ADDIE CAMPTON, TO ASSIST WITH THE NEUTRALIZING AND REPACKAGING OF THE FIBREBOARD BOXES THAT WERE AFFECTED BY THE LEAKING SHIPMENT.  THE CONTENTS OF THESE BOXES WERE TAKEN TO THE REPACKAGING DEPT AND PLACED INTO NEW OUTER BOXES.  THEN THESE BOXES WERE SENT ON TO THEIR DESTINATION.  A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED FROM THE SHIPPER ON THE 14 OUNCE BOTTLE OF "ERUSTICATOR" DUE TO THE PH READING OF 0.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION OF THE BOX REVEALED THE FOLLOWING: THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS DUE TO FRICTION TYPE CONTAINERS WITH NO POSITIVE MEANS OF CLOSURE AND IMPROPER ORIENTATION OF THE CONTENTS.  THE CONTAMINATED BOXES WERE PLACED INSIDE PLASTIC BAGS AND RESEALED FOR DISPOSAL.

column42: BATTERY, ELECTRIC STORAGE, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, WITH AUTOMOBILE (OR SPECIFICALLY NAMED SELF-PROPELLED VEHICLE OR MECHANICAL APPARATUS)
column168: ON 4-21-93, RAMP SUPERVISOR, DON LENGEFELD, REPORTED A SHIPMENT THAT WAS EMITTING A VAPOR.  THIS WAS LOCATED IN BELLY THREE FO AIRCRAFT 793AL AT GATE B-53.  UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENT, I, TONY FRYE, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR, ENTERED THE BELLY TO INVESTIGATE THE SHIPMENT IN QUESTION.  I DID NOT SEE ANY VAPOR IN THE BELLY.  I FOUND A SHIPMENT THAT WAS LOADED ON ITS SIDE.  THIS WAS A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH A SKID ATTACHED TO THE BOTOTM. THERE WAS A PLASTIC PIECE ON BOTH SIDES OF THE FIBERBOARD BOX THAT COULD BE REMOVED.  ONE OF THESE HAD FALLEN OUT.  THE INNER CONTENTS WERE WARM TO THE TOUCH.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS REMOVED FROM THE BELLY AND RETURNED TO THE HAZMAT SORT FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION.  ONCE ARRIVING BACK AT THE HAZMAT SORT, JEFF HOSTETLER, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR AND I STARTED OPENING THE FIBERBOARD BOX.  THERE WERE TWO METAL BANDS AROUND THE SKID WHICH ATTACHED THE FIBERBOARD BOX.  THESE WERE REMOVED TO TAKE THE FIBERBOARD BOX OFF TO GET TO THE INNER CONTENTS.  THERE WAS A LARGE POWER UNIT INSIDE THAT CONTAINED FOUR BATTERIES.  WE FOUND SOME LIQUID INSIDE THE PACKING MATERIAL ON THE BOTTOM OF THE POWER UNIT.  JEFF PH'D THIS AND RECEIVED A READING BETWEEN 2 AND 5 WHICH MAKES THE MATERIAL ACIDIC.  THERE WERE FOUR BATTERIES FOUND IN THE BOTTOM OF THIS POWER UNIT.  THE TWO LOCATED TOWARD THE OUTER EDGES WERE BULGING OUTWARD.  THERE WAS SOME LIQUID LEAKING FROM AROUND THE TOP OF ONE OF THESE.  THIS MATERIAL WAS PH'D.  THE SAME READING WAS OBTAINED AS PREVIOUSLY LISTED.  THESE BATTERIES WERE SET UP IN A SERIES.  ALL THE WIRING WAS REMOVED AND PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THAT ITS CONTENTS WERE REGULATED AS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THIS SHIPMENT IS AT THE HAZMAT SORT IN THE SECURITY CAGE PENDING RELEASE BY THE FAA.

SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SA/HM) S. BALANCE WAS NOTIFIED BY B. STINE THAT CONTAINER (NONU 37008) NEAR THE "B" LEAD IN TH TOFC WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE BACK SEAL ALONG THE BASE.  SA/HM BALLANCE RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THERE WAS AN APPROXIMATE 2 DROPS PER MINUTE LEAK.  THE CONTAINER WAS LOADED WITH OIL AND DIESEL CONTAMINATED FILTERS AND SOIL.  THE CONTAINER WAS FILLED OVER A 2 MONTH PERIOD.  DURING THIS TIME THERE HAD BEEN EXTREME RAINS.  IT WAS DETERMINED THE TOP OPENINGS WERE LEFT OPEN WHICH ALLOWED WATER TO SETTLE INSIDE.  THE WATER MIXED WITH CONTENTS AND BEGAN LEAKING THROUGH THE BACK DOOR ALONG THE BOTTOM SEAL. M. EVANS, MANAGER, MECHANICAL MAINTENANCE WAS REQUESTED TO FILL THE CONTAINER WITH MORE SOIL TO ABSORB THE WATER.  THIS WAS COMPLETED AND THE CONTAINER WAS MONITORED FOR FURTHER LEAKAGE.  NO FURTHER LEAKS WERE NOTED AND CAR WAS RELEASED FOR FURTHER TRANSPORTATION.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: HERMAN COLEMAN, MY TRANSPORT DRIVER, WAS MAKING A RIGHT TURN ONTO THE ON RAMP OF I 95 IN SELMA, NC.  THE TRUCK AND TANK OVERTURNED WHILE HE WAS MAKING THE TURN.  THE DRIVER WAS CHARGED WITH EXCEEDING SAFE SPEED.  HE DID NOT FEEL THAT HE WAS GOING TO FAST.  HE FELT THAT THE LOAD MUST HAVE SHIFTED.  AFTER REVIEWING THE INCIDENT I FEEL LIKE IT MAY HAVE BEEN A COMBINATION OF BOTH.  MY DRIVER IS FAMILIAR WITH THE TURN BECAUSE HE MAKES THE SAME TURN ALMOST EVERY DAY HE DRIVES.  HOWEVER HE MAY HAVE BEEN GOING TOO FAST AND THE LOAD SHIFTED UNUSUALLY HARD WHICH CAUSED THE TRUCK TO OVER TURN.  I HAVE IN THE PART AND AGAIN AFTER THE ACCIDENT WARNED ALL DRIVERS ABOUT MAKING PROPER TURNS AND THE POSSIBILITIES OF SHIFTING LOADS.  MY DRIVER WAS NOT HURT.  EMERGENCY RESPONSE PEOPLE WERE CALLED AFTER THE ACCIDENT.  AFTER MY DRIVER CALLED ME, I WENT TO THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT. THE PRODUCT IN OUR TANK WAS PUMPED INTO ANOTHER TANK.  I CONTACTED JAMES PAUL EDWARDS INC. TO CLEAN THE 904 GALLON SPILL.  THE CONTAMINATED SOIL (394.91 TON) WAS TAKEN TO SOILWORKS RT.1 BOX 280 D ZEBULON NC.27597
column172: Tank trailer, semi-trailer or full trailer (two axles)

column168: THIS PARCEL WAS DISCOVERED IN AN INBOUND TRAILER IN THE PRIMARY LOAD.  ONE OF FOUR 1 GALLON CONTAINERS HAD A RUPTURED TOP.  THE DAMAGED PORTION WAS SENT TO THE HAZARDOUS CAGE WHILE THE OTHER THREE CONTAINERS WERE REPACKED ACCORDING TO UPS SPECIFICATIONS AND SENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  AN ISP CARD WAS PREPARED AND SENT TO THE ORIGIN DISTRICT FOR THEIR FOLLOW UP WITH THE SHIPPER.

column42: AEROSOLS, FLAMMABLE, (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column168: PACKAGE APPARENTLY SHIFTED IN TRANSIT.  UPON OPENING THE TRAILER; THE DAMAGED PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED.  THE DAMAGED CANS HAD SPLIT AT THE SEAMS, RELEASING THE CONTENTS.  THERE WAS NO EXTERNAL LEAKAGE FROM THE BOX.  THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND THE SHIPPER CONTACTED FOR PACKAGE DISPOSITION.

ON 042193, FEDERAL RAILROAD ADMINISTRATION INSPECTOR DENNIS CAMBELL WAS INSPECTING CARS AT COADY YARD, BAYTOWN, TX.  HE DISCOVERED THE ABOVE CAR LEAKING FROM THE TOP.  HE NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER, LYONDELL PETROCHEMICAL. A TEAM FROM LYONDELL ARRIVED TO FIND THE LUG ON THE LIQUID LINE WAS LOOSE AND THE VALVE NOT CLOSED.  THIS ALLOWED INTERNAL PRESSURE TO FORCE LIQUID OUT OF THE VALVE.  LYONDELL PERSONELL RINSED THE CAR BEFORE IT WAS RELEASED.  THIS INCIDENT WAS NOT REPORTED TO CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY.  THIS CAUSED A SIGNIFICANT DELAY IN A FORMAL REPORT BEING FILED WITH THE DOT.
